<li><a href="#faq">Frequently Asked Questions</a></li>
</ul>
<h2>Chapter 1: What Is a Google Core Update (And Why Recovery Is Possible) &#123;#ch1&#125;</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="how-core-updates-differ-from-penalties">
      <span class="faq-q-text">How Core Updates Differ From Penalties</span>
      <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-a" id="how-core-updates-differ-from-penalties"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A manual action appears in Google Search Console with a specific reason and a path to resolution. Core updates do not. You will see traffic drop. You will see rankings shift. But Search Console shows no warning message.</p></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="why-recovery-is-always-possible">
      <span class="faq-q-text">Why Recovery Is Always Possible</span>
      <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-a" id="why-recovery-is-always-possible"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google confirms that sites can recover from core update impacts. John Mueller has stated that incremental improvements can show results over time. Full recovery often requires the next core update cycle for a complete re-evaluation. For official guidance, see <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/fundamentals/google-core-updates">Google's documentation on core updates</a>.</p></div></div>
  </div>
